  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Relative Pronouns (الاسم الموصول)",
      "titleArabic": "الاسم الموصول",
      "content": [
        "Relative pronouns connect a noun to a descriptive clause. In Arabic, the relative pronoun must agree with its antecedent in gender and number.",
        "The clause following the relative pronoun is called صلة الموصول (the relative clause) and must contain a returning pronoun (ضمير عائد) that refers back to the antecedent."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "الَّذِي - who/which (masculine singular)",
        "الَّتِي - who/which (feminine singular)",
        "الَّذِينَ - who/which (masculine plural)",
        "اللَّاتِي / اللَّوَاتِي - who/which (feminine plural)",
        "اللَّذَانِ - who/which (masculine dual)",
        "اللَّتَانِ - who/which (feminine dual)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "الرَّجُلُ الَّذِي ذَهَبَ", "english": "The man who went" },
        { "arabic": "الْمَرْأَةُ الَّتِي كَتَبَتْ", "english": "The woman who wrote" },
        { "arabic": "الْكِتَابُ الَّذِي قَرَأْتُهُ", "english": "The book which I read (it)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Returning Pronoun",
      "titleArabic": "الضمير العائد",
      "content": [
        "In relative clauses, a pronoun must refer back to the noun being described. This is called the returning pronoun (ضمير عائد)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "The returning pronoun agrees with the antecedent in gender and number",
        "It can be attached to a verb, noun, or preposition in the relative clause",
        "Example: الكتاب الذي قرأتُهُ - the هُ refers back to الكتاب"
      ]
    }
  ],
